not saying it isn't incredibly powerful, but (1) I believe it's still the case (please correct if I'm wrong) that it's not possible to render via Nanite w/o running meshes through an offline preprocessor. This makes it only suitable for certain types of gamedev, not general HPG rendering

And (2) in "legacy" graphics APIs (both SW and HW) I as an end-user (non-hand-optimizer) had a huge amount of control over how rendering happens. Nanite is programmable for a handful of Epic rendering gurus, and for us end-users it is a black box for doing certain types of game rendering v fast

Not saying Nanite isn't amazing, I'm saying it would /also/ be cool if there was a general-purpose end-user-programmable rendering API that could do some fraction of what Nanite can achieve. But IMO that's impossible today because of how limited GPU programming infrastructure is.

You start a company in order to make profits and, ideally, become rich. You, the owner, take the largest share of personal profit from your company. You hire people to run and maintain the machinery of your business. You pay them as little as possible in order to maximize your own profits and the

money that can go to expanding your business. You extract the time and labor from employees in order to make a profit. In order to buy more machinery, resources, and space as you expand your business, you have to hire more people. 

The owner, along with other owners and wealthy people, is

incentivized to keep wages low. Is incentivized to keep benefits/health insurance/retirement plans cheap or nonexistent. Is incentivized to maintain a large low wage labor force which lacks upward mobility to continually exploit for profit. Is incentivized to maintain a myth about the American Dream

and upward mobility in the media, the media which is owned by wealthy private interests. Is incentivized to suppress labor unions. Is incentivized to divide and conquer the low wage work force along different lines in order to suppress labor union support/class awareness. Is incentivized to

maintain expensive educational gatekeeping. Is incentivized to suppress any approximation of working class democracy by appropriating elected representatives through different legal and illegal means and through things like gerrymandering, PACS, Super PACS, lobbying, and media influence on politics.

Is capitalism a Ponzi scheme? Did Adam Smith talk about how many poor workers it takes to support the lifestyle of one rich person? Capitalism is not incentivized to generate an egalitarian society through technological innovation. Capitalism is not incentivized to generate justice or economic

fairness. Capitalism is incentivized to generate propaganda and economic exploitation. 

The only way to escape the rat race in capitalism is to join the wealthy class and exploit other people for profit. The system is built to suppress revolutions and reforms that do not serve the interests of

capital. The only way to gain power and influence that could help working Americans is to join the capital class to varying degrees and to change your principles and views on ethics. Capitalistic systems can easily become economically unstable through deregulation and the gambling of the capital

class (before relying on military force to bail them out), but in a social and cultural sense they are extremely stable. The Citizen Kane Effect is built into capitalism.

In a society in which sixty percent of Americans live paycheck to paycheck. In a society in which ninety percent of people born

into the working class never leave the working class, we find American liberty, egalitarianism, and justice in movies and tv shows and nowhere else in actual lived experience. There used to be an old idea that people should only be indentured servants for a number of years before being able to own

their own land and business. In the America of today people are indentured servants for life and are expected to be grateful for the low quality jobs that business owners provide. All the while as business owners continue to undermine democracy and social programs for the working class. The American

Dream? Is exactly that: just a dream. Wake up.

It's interesting, even google seems to have a really biased answer.

Race realists tend to believe individuals have traits that are deeply rooted in culture and biology. It's possible that an ethnic group has a nontrivial average difference vs another ethnic group on things like violence and IQ etc.
Google of course restates it in a way that seems to discredit it: "inherent often immutable differences"

But race realists don't deny tremendous variation within groups. 

One specific Samoan American may have a higher IQ than one specific Indian American, but it still may be the case that IAs on average have higher IQs than SAs.

I certainly wouldn't deny it's likely true that expression of race realism often goes together with a lot of other views.

 Many open RRs do seem to have a bias/animosity towards nonwhites and conservative/libertarian views generally. But again they don't necessarily always go together.

ir demarcándolo dentro del dominio operatorio de cada ciencia, en función del grado en que las operaciones del sujeto queden neutralizadas, segregando teoremas que son independientes del sujeto. Desde este esquema hilemórfico (y no el de sujeto-objeto) ya no tiene sentido hablar de "la ciencia" en

en sentido descripcionista o teoreticista, como modelos que dan información objetiva de lo real, sino que se habla en términos circularistas, en donde las ciencias se basan fundamentalmente en operaciones que transforman y alteran lo real y nuestra percepción de dicha realidad (hiperrealismo).
